paintings.name: The Virgin and Child Surrounded by Eight Angels
paintings.description: This is a captivating masterpiece that transports viewers to the ethereal realm of Renaissance art. Painted by Marco Zoppo in 1455, this oil on canvas print captures the divine bond between the Virgin Mary and her infant son, Jesus Christ. In this enchanting scene, eight angels gracefully encircle the central figures, their celestial presence adding an aura of serenity and purity.

paintings.name: Maria Lactans
paintings.description: That this is not an everyday scene between mother and child is revealed by the halos, so-called nimbuses, glowing in gold, which surround the heads of mother and child. In addition, the title of the painting proves that this is a particular type of depiction of Mary - Maria Lactans, the nursing Mother of God. This image motif already appears in ancient Egyptian culture, where the goddess Isis breastfeeds the Horus boy. Mary, like Isis before her, passes on divine power with her milk. In Christianity, the image type is also symbolic of fertility and is said to demonstrate a deep humanity of the baby Jesus through the act of breastfeeding.

paintings.name: Christ at the Column
paintings.description: The image depicts a solitary male figure, representing Jesus Christ himself, bound to a column with ropes as a form of punishment. The artist skillfully portrays Christ's suffering through his pained expression and the presence of the crown of thorns upon his head. Looking up towards heaven, he symbolizes both physical and spiritual agony endured during his crucifixion. This Renaissance-era painting exemplifies Antonello da Messina's mastery in capturing human emotion and conveying profound religious themes.

paintings.name: Ritratto d’uoma
paintings.description: The portrait was given the title  Condottiere (the mercenary commander) during the late nineteenth century because of the willful determination in its sitter's face. It entered Napoleon Ill's collection in 1865, fetching 113,500 francs at a sale at the Pourtales-Gorgier Gallery. The large sum paid for it is proof of the high esteem in which the Italian painter was held by the mid-nineteenth century. Its new title betrays the reason for renewed interest in the portrait: it provided an aesthetic medium through which to identify with the power-hungry usurpers, the heroes and new, strong men of the Renaissance, with their ebullient, nouveau-riche style and dramatic rise to power.

paintings.name: Portrait of a Man
paintings.description: The painting is one of a series of portraits executed by Bellini around 1500. The series culminated in the portrait of Doge Loredan.

paintings.name: Blessing Christ
paintings.description: This painting is usually identified with the 'Portrait of the Saviour' mentioned in 1648 by Ridolfi in the Agostinian convent of Santo Stefano in Venice. On the one hand this Christ is still associated with the master's first works, marked by a pathetic resentment that would soon disappear to leave space for the elevated 'classical' melancholy; on the other, Bellini demonstrates his capacity to juxtapose the suggestions of Mantegna's style and those generically Paduan post-Donatello influences with a concept of light that is not only extraordinary but emphatically personal.

paintings.name: The Crucifixion of the Parlament of Paris
paintings.description: This work was executed for the Grande Chambre of the Parlement of Paris and is attributed to an unknown master, often referred to as the Master of Dreux Budé, a painter native of Flanders or the north of France. The artwork is a cross between a polyptych and an altarpiece and features a single, united landscape that depicts the Paris of that time. The painting is part of the collection at the Musée du Louvre in Paris and is housed in the Department of Paintings.

paintings.name: The Madonna and Child surrounded by Six Angels
paintings.description: The painting you've shown is titled 'The Madonna and Child Surrounded by Six Angels, St. Anthony of Padua, St. John the Evangelist' by Stefano di Giovanni, known as Sassetta. Created between 1437 and 1444, the piece is executed in tempera and gold on poplar wood and measures 207 cm by 118 cm. It's part of the Louvre Museum's collection and is located in Room 709 of the Department of Paintings. This work is a fine example of Sassetta's religious art and is part of the Saint Francis Altarpiece. For more details, you can visit the Louvre's website or the artwork's page on Wikimedia Commons.

paintings.name: Salle des Sept-Mètres
paintings.description: The image you've provided is of a triptych painted by the Master of 1333, an anonymous artist active in the 14th century. This work of art is from the Italian school and is characterized by religious themes, depicting scenes like the Annunciation and the Coronation of the Virgin. It's made with tempera and gold on panel and measures 135 cm in height and 73 cm in width. You can find this triptych in room 4 of the Italian paintings section at the Louvre Museum, known as the salle des Sept-Mètres. For more information, you can visit the page on Wikimedia Commons dedicated to this triptych.

paintings.name: The Virgin and Child Surrounded by Saint Benedict of Nursie and Saint Quentin with Two Angels
paintings.description: The artwork portrays the Virgin Mary and the infant Jesus, flanked by saints and angels, capturing the religious art style of the period.
